'''Thomas Schnauz''' is an American television producer and television writer. His credits include ''[[The X-Files]]'', ''[[The Lone Gunmen (TV series)|The Lone Gunmen]]'', ''[[Night Stalker (TV series)|Night Stalker]]'', ''[[Reaper (TV series)|Reaper]]'', ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', and ''[[Better Call Saul]]''.
==Personal life== Schnauz was born in New Jersey.<ref name=WritersRoom>{{cite web|title=The Writers Room cast members|url=http://www.sundance.tv/series/the-writers-room/cast/thomas-schnauz|website=Sundance TV|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> He attended [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]], where he first met fellow student [[Vince Gilligan]].<ref name=WritersRoom /> Schnauz graduated from Tisch in 1988.<ref>https://www.nyu.edu/alumni.magazine/issue17/17_culture_credits.html</ref>
==Career== Schnauz started his career in various production jobs. His first screenplay was called "[[Spirits in Passing]]". He eventually joined Vince Gilligan on the writing staffs of ''[[The X-Files]]'' and its spinoff show, ''[[The Lone Gunmen (TV series)|The Lone Gunmen]]''.<ref name=WritersRoom /> He also co-wrote the screenplays for the 2008 film ''[[Otis (film)|Otis]]'' and the 2008 television film ''[[Infected (2008 film)|Infected]]''. In 2010, he re-teamed with Gilligan on ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', where he remained through the show's 2013 conclusion.
Schnauz signed a two-year overall deal with [[Sony Pictures Television]] in November 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2014/01/breaking-bads-tom-schnauz-inks-overall-deal-with-sony-tv-joins-better-call-saul-660785/|title=‘Breaking Bad’s Tom Schnauz Inks Overall Deal With Sony TV, Joins ‘Better Call Saul’|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=2014-01-09|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-11-24|language=en-US}}</ref>
Currently, Schnauz serves as co-executive producer on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]'s ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' spinoff series ''[[Better Call Saul]].''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/breaking-bad-writers-join-better-call-saul-staff-1200981189/ |title=‘Breaking Bad’ Writers Join ‘Better Call Saul’ Staff |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |work=Variety |date=December 20, 2013 |accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> He has written and/or directed a number of its episodes including [[Pimento (Better Call Saul)|"Pimento"]], the penultimate episode of the show's first season, which received critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bowman|first1=Donna|title=Better Call Saul: 'Pimento'|url=https://www.avclub.com/tvclub/better-call-saul-pimento-217233|accessdate=26 April 2015|work=The A.V. Club|date=30 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Sepinwall|first1=Alan|title='Better Call Saul' - 'Pimento': Shut the door, have a seat|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-better-call-saul-pimento-shut-the-door-have-a-seat|website=HitFix||date=30 March 2015|accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>
In April 2015, it was reported that he had been tapped to write the screenplay for "a revisionist take" on [[Jack and the Beanstalk]], also to be produced by Vince Gilligan.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Disney, ' Breaking Bad' Creator Vince Gilligan Taking Another Whack At Jack And The Beanstalk|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/breaking-bad-vince-gilligan-jack-and-the-beanstalk-1201414639|website=Deadline Hollywood | date=22 April 2015 | accessdate=26 April 2015}}</ref>
In 2019, Schnauz joined other WGA writers in firing their agents as part of the [[Writers Guild of America|WGA's]] stand against the [[Association of Talent Agents|ATA]] and the unfair practice of [[Movie packaging|packaging]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Patton Oswalt, David Simon, Danny Zuker, More WGA Members Post Termination Letters |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/wga-members-termination-letters-1203189062/ |publisher=Variety}}</ref>
